# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1880-troy-trojans-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1879-troy-trojans-season] The 1879 season was the National League debut for the **Troy Trojans**.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1879-troy-trojans-season] They finished the season 19–56, last in the league.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-boston-red-caps-season] The **1880 Boston Red Caps** was the tenth season of the franchise.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-buffalo-bisons-season] The **1880 Buffalo Bisons** finished the season with a 24–58 record, good for seventh place in the National League.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] The **1880 Cincinnati Stars season** was the first and only season for the Cincinnati Stars, a professional baseball franchise competing in the National League (NL).
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] The club replaced the defunct Cincinnati Reds that had competed in the NL during 1876–1879.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] The Stars finished last in the eight-team NL with a record of 21–59, 44 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Team president Justus Thorner resigned in early July, with vice-president Nathan Menderson selected as his successor.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] At the end of the season, the team was kicked out of the league for their refusal to stop selling beer and renting out their park on Sundays.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] A new Cincinnati Reds franchise joined the American Association two years later.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] During the off-season, Cincinnati signed catcher John Clapp, who had played with the Buffalo Bisons in the previous season.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Clapp was also named the manager of the team.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Deacon White, who was the Reds catcher in 1878 and 1879, moved to the outfield.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Other off-season signings included Hick Carpenter of the Syracuse Stars to play third base, while the Stars had rookies at first base, John Reilly, and second base, Pop Smith.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Clapp and Blondie Purcell led the team offensively, as Clapp had a .282 average with a homer and 20 RBI and 33 runs scored, while Purcell hit .292 with a homer and 24 RBI, along with 48 runs.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Will White led the NL with 42 losses; however, he had a good ERA of 2.14.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Cincinnati got off to a miserable start, having a record of only 6–26 in their first 32 games, which included lopsided losses of 20–7 and 15–1 to the White Stockings, and 13–0 to the Worcester Worcesters during that span.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cincinnati-stars-season] Cincinnati never got it together during the season, and finished in last place in their only season, 44 games behind the first place White Stockings.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-cleveland-blues-season] The **1880 Cleveland Blues** finished the season at 47–37, good enough for a third-place finish in the National League.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The **1880 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through October 1, 1880, and saw the Chicago White Stockings as the pennant winner of the fifth season of the National League.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 season is known for the first two major league perfect games in history, as well as being the only perfect games in the 19th century.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Thrown by Lee Richmond and John Ward, these two perfect games were thrown in the span of five days, the shortest amount of time between two perfect games (the next closest is currently 20 days between Dallas Braden's May 9 and Roy Halladay's and May 29, 2010 perfect games).
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] A perfect game would not be seen again in the Major Leagues for 24 years when Cy Young threw his perfect game in 1904.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, the Cincinnati Reds and Syracuse Stars disbanded, and were replaced by the Cincinnati Stars and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the Stars' only major league season.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The 1880 schedule consisted of 84 games for all eight teams of the National League.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the previous season and would be used until 1883.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 1, featuring a doubleheader between the Providence Grays and Worcester Worcesters.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] Eight tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons, Cincinnati Stars, and Providence Grays had three tie games each.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, and Worcester Worcesters had two tie games each.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans leave the Putnam Grounds (where they played their inaugural seasons) and move to the Haymakers' Grounds, where they would play for two seasons through 1881.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-major-league-baseball-season] The Troy Trojans begin to host a few games at Riverside Park in nearby Greenbush, New York, playing on September 11.
[src:1880-troy-trojans-season/1880-troy-trojans-season] The **1880 Troy Trojans** improved slightly from the previous season, finishing with a 41–42 record and in 4th place in the National League.
